# Maven Notes

## 1. What is Maven?
Maven is a **build automation and project management tool** used mainly for Java projects. It uses an XML file called `pom.xml` (Project Object Model) to manage:
- Project dependencies (JARs)
- Build lifecycle (compile, test, package, deploy)
- Project structure (standard directory layout)
- Plugins for various tasks (testing, packaging, reporting)

---

## 2. Why Maven? (Why not manage JARs manually?)

| Without Maven | With Maven |
|---|---|
| Manually download JARs and add to classpath | Dependencies auto-downloaded from repository |
| No standard project structure | Follows a standard folder structure (easy for any dev to understand) |
| Manual dependency conflict handling | Automatic **transitive dependency** management (if A needs B, Maven auto-fetches B) |
| Manual build steps (compile, test, package separately) | Single command runs the entire build lifecycle |
| Hard to share/reproduce builds across machines/teams | `pom.xml` ensures same build config everywhere (consistency) |
| No easy versioning of libraries | Dependencies specified with exact versions in `pom.xml` |

**In short:** Maven = standardization + automation + dependency management. This is why it's preferred over manually managing JARs, and it's also more structured than tools like Ant (which requires you to write build steps manually with no dependency management).

